A Spring Concert Like No Other
West Essex Band Performs Virtual Spring Concert
The continuing social distancing environment did not prevent the students of the West Essex High
School Band Program from showcasing their talents this Spring. High School Band Director Anthony
Fabrizio coordinated a “virtual” concert, where 11 solo and small ensemble performances were enjoyed
by students, their families, school administrators and Board of Education members via Google Meets on
April 30.

From an Email sent by Superintendent of Schools; Damion Macioci:

Dear West Essex Community

I hope this email finds you well. As we approach week 6 of distance learning, our staff remains committed to serving our students, staying positive, and working together towards brighter times. Although we are not physically on our campus, our students and families will continue to be in our hearts and minds. In an effort to bring a smile to your day, please view the attached WE Strong Video.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8gLaZi6xWEI&feature=youtu.be

We miss you and wish to see you soon!

Warm regards,

Damion Macioci, Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Calling all West Essex faculty and students..

Right now our world is going through something it has never seen before. In a time in which negativity is surrounding us, let's work together and show our community the positivity of West Essex!

The SAVE Promise Club is encouraging all faculty and students to paint a rock and label it with a word that is inspirational or meaningful to you at this time...When we return to school, please bring your rock and we will put them all in the center of the circle near the flagpole to show our unity and strength in a time our nation needed some optimism.

Have a question? Feel free to email Mrs. Corcoran at scorcora@westex.org. Please also feel free to send pictures of your painted rocks. We would love to see what you have created!

post_text:
This past Sunday, March 8th, our very own West Essex Middle School Band Director, Rick Fitzke had the pleasure of conducting the NJSMA Intermediate Region Concert Band. The 80 member ensemble was made up of the finest 7th, 8th and 9th grade musicians from northern New Jersey, after a successful audition process back in February. Mr. Fitzke has been a force at WEMS for the past 28 years, where he lives by the credo "I don't make great music with my students. I make great students through music."

Pictured are 9th grade band members Gianna Lodato (percussion) and Dante Ragusa (tuba) both of whom performed with the Symphonic Winds on March 8th, after having successfully auditioned back in February. Also pictured is Mr. Fitzke, WEMS Director of Bands, who conducted the Region Concert Band. Not pictured: Anthony Fabrizio, WEHS Director of Bands.

post_text: On Thursday, March 5th, Commercial Photographer, John Paul "Bud" Endress, visited West Essex High School Digital Photography students. Mr. Endress, Owner of John Paul Endress Photography, was a commercial studio photographer in New York City for over 40 years. He specialized in automobiles, airplanes, special effects, food, editorial and still life. He shot everything from Ads to Ferarari. Mr. Endress resides in Essex Fells, NJ where he is well known within the community. He currently has four photos in the Museum of Modern Art's permanent collection.

post_text:
The Symphonic Winds ensemble have been very fortunate to have Mr. Bruce Yurko conduct and rehearse them three times this year. The Symphonic Winds played Mr. Yurko's piece, Night Dances, in the fall and he came in to conduct the group and rehearse with them before their performance. He returned after winter break to work on another one of his pieces, In Memoriam: Kristina, which they will be performing at Carnegie Hall on March 16th! Tickets are available on this link: https://www.carnegiehall.org/Events

Photo Credits to Kathy Shwiff

post_text:
The West Essex Middle School held its 14th annual 7th Grade Hero Assembly on Thursday, February 13th.

The class of 2020 did an amazing job writing about their heroes. 7 students shared their "letter to their Hero" with their peers, teachers and the heroes that attended the assembly.

Dr. Donlevie welcomed all students and guests and introduced the program. The National Anthem was beautifully performed by Mrs. Rizzo's Choir. Ms. Riker explained what Character Education is and what the assembly was all about and 8 students read an explanation of each one of the Character Traits. Ms. Sciacchitano spoke about what it means to be a model citizen and then the student essays were read.

The Keynote Speaker this year was Teacher & West Essex Graduate;Mr. Greg Ruggiero. Mr. Ruggiero touched all audience members with his tribute to his daughter who is battling a life long illness.

post_text: NJ State Assemblyman, Brian Bergen, visited West Essex High School on Thursday, February 13th. Mr. Bergen spoke to both Middle and High School History classes on many topics including, his time at West Point and Iraq, how to go about becoming an assemblyman, how to introduce a bill, just to name a few. Mr. Bergen is the long time friend of teacher, Mr. Pat Mcglynn, who introduced his friend and helped facilitate the talks. A big thank you to Mr. Bergen for taking time out of his busy schedule to speak to West Essex Students!

On Sunday, February 9th, Jessica Coia represented West Essex High School at an Awards Luncheon held at Seton Hall University. The luncheon was held in honor of Girls and Women in Sports Day. Jessica is a 3 sport athlete lettering each season in Varsity Volleyball, Basketball and Softball.

The National Girls and Women in Sports Day (NGWSD) is an annual day of observance held during the first week of February to Acknowledge the accomplishments of female athletes, recognize the influence of sports participation for women and girls, and honor the progress and continuing struggle for equality for women in sports.

Jess is pictured here with head coach: Maria Faggiani and with her parents.

post_text: West Essex Middle School held its very first COOKIE WITH A COP event today, January 28th in the Middle School gym. Police Officers from Essex Fells, Fairfield, North Caldwell and Roseland attended the event designed to allow students to become more familiar and comfortable with local law enforcement. Students were able to engage in casual conversation with the officers while enjoying cookies provided by Pomptonian Food Service. The Chiefs of Police from each district addressed the students and encouraged them to reach out at any time for any reason.

post_text: In honor of Martin Luther King Day yesterday, West Essex Middle and High School Students had the great honor of having guest speaker Aris Tzoundi come to the High School Auditorium. A North Caldwell residient, Mr. Tzoundi is the epitome of the modern American Dream. He was born in Cameroon where he was struck by the country's need for development. Mr. Tzoundi graduated from The Wharton School of The University of Pennsylvania and is currently a senior manager at Ernst and Young in New York. You can read more about him by clicking this link: https://executivemba.wharton.upenn.edu/story/african-real-estate-development-venture-makes-big-impact-cameroon/

post_text:
On Saturday, January 19, the boys and girls fencing team competed in their district tournament.

The boys team came in 3rd overall and will advance to the first round of the state tournament on February 3.

The boys Epee team placed 3rd, boys foil team placed 2nd and girls Sabre team placed 2nd overall. Each squad will advance to the state tournament in late February.

In addition, senior Evie Klein placed 4th, junior Matthew Sun placed 3rd, senior Ahren Alberto placed 2nd, junior Ethan Wiederhorn placed 2nd, freshman Audrey Baker placed 1st, senior Robin Hu placed 1st and senior Kevin Baker placed 1st in their respective weapons. These fencers will advance to the individual tournament on March 1st.

Congratulations to all of the fencers for their outstanding performance this past Saturday.

Click here for a link to the Patch article: https://patch.com/new-jersey/caldwells/njsiaa-district-2-high-school-fencing-championship

post_text:
Congratulations to all 8 of our North Jersey Area Band audition winners this year! All of these students spent many hours preparing to audition against students from all over North Jersey to earn a spot in either the select Wind Ensemble, or the Symphonic Band. In addition, four of our students were chosen for coveted first chair positions between both groups. All of these students perform in the West Essex High School Symphonic Winds ensemble.
James Humphrey (Sophomore) - Symphonic Band - Bass Clarinet
Gianna Lodato (Freshman) - Symphonic Band - Percussion
Andrew Marino (Sophomore) - Wind Ensemble - 1st Chair Mallets
Caroline McElhannon (Sophomore) - Symphonic Band - Flute
Ryan Polizzi (Sophomore) - Symphonic Band - 1st Chair Trombone
Gabriel Ruszala (Junior) - Wind Ensemble - 1st Chair Trombone
TJ Viola (Senior) - Wind Ensemble - 1st Chair French Horn
Julia Zon (Junior) - Symphonic Band - Percussion
Jimmy Alamia (Junior) - Symphonic Band - Timpani

post_text: The annual Senior Citizen Breakfast and Concert was held on Wednesday, December 4th in the West Essex High School Cafeteria and Auditorium. The Arts department came together to create this wonderful community event. Students from the Culinary classes prepared and served food for over 100 guests! Dining music was provided by the Jazz Band, with vocals by Madison Rombough! During Breakfast Seniors were also treated to performances by both the ladies and men's a capella choirs and by the Varsity Dance Team. After breakfast the guests were ushered into the brand new auditorium for performances by the band and choir.

post_text:
Turkey Drive!

The Cooking 4 A Cause Club will be sponsoring a “Frozen Turkey Drive” here at West Essex High School on Sunday, November 18th between 11:00 am and 2:00 pm. Please drop off frozen turkeys or turkey breasts at the entrance of the school along with any holiday canned goods you can spare. Just pull up to the main entrance of the high school and the students will happily collect your donations. Additional items we would gladly accept are canned and boxed goods such as gravy, cranberry sauce, instant mashed potatoes, and stuffing, though everything is appreciated. Bring that day or drop them in our food donation bin now near the front entrance. The turkeys will be delivered to the food banks (Saint Thomas More in Caldwell and Toni’s Kitchen in Montclair) for distribution in time for Thanksgiving. Please help support those in the community who are less fortunate.

post_text: Yesterday, one of our own teachers, Ms. Samantha Minnella conquered the 49th TCS New York City Marathon. She raised money through donations in support of Memorial Sloan Kettering and was surrounded by 50,000 other marathon racers. Samantha is now a part of the elite group of people to complete such an unbelievable mental, physical, and emotional challenge. Samantha finished the race in a little over 4 hours. Enduring months of training with a rigorous teaching and coaching schedule is something to be proud of. Congratulations on this outstanding achievement!

Calling all West Essex Alumni Veterans!
West Essex High School is reaching out to all West Essex alumni who have served in any military branch during war or times of peace. We are hoping to honor any and all West Essex veterans during an event on Wednesday, November 6. The event will consist of a brunch, a 30-minute honorary assembly, and classroom visits by veterans. West Essex veterans are cordially invited to participate in all three components or whichever they choose.

We are asking for your assistance in identifying, locating, and contacting WEHS veterans. Please reach out to any West Essex veterans, or families of veterans, and ask them to contact Caesar Diliberto at (973) 228-1200 extension 1200, cdiliber@westex.org; or Andrea Trombino at extension 1217, atrombin@westex.org.

post_text:
On the 27th of September, the West Essex Chinese Club went to a Chinese Arts and Culture Workshop hosted by Rutgers University. The workshops consisted of several different stations showcasing Chinese culture and arts. The stations included activities such as Chinese calligraphy, water and ink painting, paper cutting, kung fu, traditional instruments and a lot more.

Each station gave Chinese Club members a hands on experience of the unique culture of China, which is what the Chinese Club strives to teach West Essex. These experiences are vital, as they allow members to experience what a textbook can’t offer. Some club members practiced Martial arts and Lion Dance, as well as some other hands on crafts. The members enjoyed having a firsthand view of Chinese culture, helping them gain a better worldview.

The SAVE (Students Against Violence Everywhere) Promise Clubs are an important part of the Sandy Hook Promise. The clubs are established and run by students and can be a powerful approach to preventing gun violence because they recognize the unique position that students have in advancing the safety of their own school and community.

The SOCKTOBER event is taking place during the entire month of October at the Middle School. The Builders Club is collecting socks as well as toiletries to create hygiene kits. All donations will go to local shelters. The items will be collected in large boxes located in front of the library.

This May, 24 senior students were a part of an amazing service opportunity! The students volunteered to work in Kissimmee, Florida at Give Kids the World Village. This Village houses over 280 families at a time that have a child with a life-threatening disease. Students volunteered to work in shifts for different jobs to help run the property. The property is entirely volunteer run and families stay for a week long vacation with all expenses paid.

Click here to watch video of the event:.https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gZH8iC8_rJM&feature=youtu.be

post_text:
A Big Shout Out to West Essex High School Senior Madelin Morales for being named 2019 Presidential Scholar. Madelin is one of only 161 students nationwide to receive this honor. The White House Commission on Presidential Scholars selects scholars annually based on academic success, artistic and technical excellence, essays, school evaluations and transcripts, as well as evidence of community service, leadership and demonstrated commitment to high ideals. Madelyn is one of the top 20 Scholars in the Arts!

During the application process, candidates are asked to select a teacher or instructor who has influenced them most significantly during their journey. Madelin selected Ms. Donna Mateyka. Ms. Mateyka was honored as a Presidential Scholars most influential teacher for her dedication and commitment to the success of her students.

post_text:
Middle School students paid $1.00 per yard to duct tape their principal to the cafeteria wall! All in an effort to raise money for the Summit Speech School;
a school that provides educational and therapeutic support services to children who are deaf or hard of hearing. A student at WEMS has a brother that attends the school so the cause was close to heart. The fundraiser raised $170, which the school is going to use toward the purchases of acoustic paneling.

Students also had a children's book and stuffed animal collection. They collected 20 books and 10 stuffed animals. The school places hearing aides in the stuffed animals so the children have stuffed animals like them.

For the Duct Tape event students paid $1 per yard of tape. WE sold "yards" in advance during the lunch periods during the weeks leading to the event. On May 2nd, students were called down to tape the principal. One 7th grade student donated $20 for 20 yards of tape. An 8th grader donated $27 for 27 yards of tape.

All of the tape was generously donated by Decker Tape in Fairfield, New Jersey.

post_text: Congratulations to Gabriel Ruszala (10th grade) for winning an audition to be the 1st chair trombone player in the New Jersey All-State Jazz Band. Each year many high school musicians audition and only 3 tenor trombones are selected. Gabriel will be performing with other top high school musicians under the direction of long time Count Basie Big Band drummer, Mr. Dennis Mackrel. You can see Gabriel with the All-State Jazz Band next fall, November 15th, at NJPAC.

post_text: On Wednesday, April 17th the World Language department held its National World Language Honor Societies Induction Ceremony. Students were inducted into the Chinese, French, Italian, Latin, and Spanish honor societies in a ceremony held in the high school auditorium. Supervisor, Mrs. Laura Drago welcomed the audience and introduced the advisers. Each language had this year's officers as presenters of the new inductees. Several students performed songs and poetry readings in their foreign language.

West Essex High School Robotics Club members Dylan Huff and Kyle Wolfberg, came in 3rd place, in the Technology Problem Solving category, at the Technology Student Associations state conference this past weekend. 60 schools from throughout the state participated in over 35 competitions involving science, technology, engineering, math, and creativity.

With their 3rd place finish, Juniors,Dylan and Kyle have earned an opportunity to compete at the national TSA conference at the end of June.

The Robotics Club is advised by Mr. Tim Shea and Ms. Clare Sweeney.
